as a powershell user i want  feature uniq to powershell...i  want unloop  the loop  (this feature is implemented in Regex virtual machine loop/unloop  '**backtraking**')

powershell has enriched its language with a lot of technique from other languages ​​like splating (ruby), operators (perl/bash), a lot of feature c# , ...etc. 
it is time for other languages ​​to take idea and feature from powershell
  

```
$range =  1..100

foreach($i  in $range) {
     echo  $i
     if($i -eq 50)  {
        unloop ( $i -gt 20; $i+=2 ) {
            echo "$i"
        }
     }
}
```


in this example the second _loop_ "**unloop**" backtrack  **2 step** every "_loop_" and  stop if **$i -gt 20**

comments.body:
It's also for the most part impossible to move backwards without heavily altering the code generated for a `foreach` statement.

This code:

```powershell
foreach ($a in 0...10) {
    $a
}
```

Gets translated roughly to:

```powershell
$enumerator = (0..10).GetEnumerator()
try {
    while ($enumerator.MoveNext()) {
        $a = $enumerator.Current
        $a
    }
} finally {
    ($enumerator -as [IDisposable])?.Dispose()
}
```

`IEnumerator` doesn't have a `MovePrevious` method.  Implementing `unloop` would require either switching the code gen to use indexing *only* when that's possible and throwing otherwise, or allocating a whole new array just to support it.  It would also probably have to do this for every single `foreach` statement even if no `unloop` was used, or be very strict in how it can be used (no nested script blocks).
